
Walking is one of the most familiar human behaviors, yet underlying this seemingly simple action is a complex integration of systems that can be highly informative. Gait is a highly coordinated and optimized process, governed by principles that shape its stability and efficiency, and disruptions to this efficiency can manifest as pathological gait @kuoDynamicPrinciplesGait2010. Because gait represents the state of multiple underlying systems (e.g., neuromuscular, vestibular, and skeletal to name a few), it changes in recognizable patters in response to disease and decline @osobaBalanceGaitElderly2019. For example, gait speed at midlife has been linked to cognitive function and decline @rasmussenAssociationNeurocognitivePhysical2019, gait characteristics may help differentiate between types of dementia @vergheseGaitDysfunctionMild2008, and gait abornamlites can aid in diagnosing Parkinson's disease and predicting attentional decline @galnaProgressionGaitDysfunction2015 @morrisGaitRatherCognition2017. 

The ability to easily and objectively quantify gait could therefore position it as a practical, non-invasive biomarker for disease diagnosis, recovery evaluation, and rehabilitation efficacy @scheetsUseMovementSystem2007. 

Although marker-based systems are the 'gold standard' for obtaining kinematic measurements, these systems are not often accessible or practical for use outside the standard laboratory (see Introduction I for an overview of the limitations of marker-based motion capture). Markerless motion capture, enabled by recent advancements in computer vision, have potential as a much more accessible method to obtain kinematic data (see Introduction II for an overview of markerless motion capture). However, even existing markerless systems can have limitations to consider. 

Here, we present a six-camera video-based motion capture system observing walking at progressively increasing speeds, and compare it to a marker-based reference. Pose estimation software can be a meaningful source of variation, and so we further evaluate 3D reconstructions derived from three pose estimation frameworks—MediaPipe, RTMPose, and ViTPose. Thus, we can systematically characterize how tracking differences can shape downstream biomechanical measurements. 






